{"questionId":"27975","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>At Mirabooka Primary School, a survey found that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>68</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of students have a dog and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of&nbsp;students have a cat. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>14</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of students have both a dog and a cat.</p>\n<p>This information can be represented in the following Venn diagram, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi></math>&nbsp;represent the percentage of students within each region.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/70d061334915aadefa71688aa34b40032252c269.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Each year, one student is chosen randomly to be the school captain of Mirabooka&nbsp;Primary School.</p>\n<p>Tim is using a binomial distribution to make predictions about how many of the next <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math>&nbsp;school captains will own a dog. He assumes that the percentages found in the survey will&nbsp;remain constant for future years and that the events “being a school captain” and “having&nbsp;a dog” are independent.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Use Tim’s model to find the probability that in the next 10 years</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>more than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> school captains have a dog.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>984</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>984497</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>%</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27975","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.4d.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"more than 3 school captains have a dog.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.8—Binomial distribution"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}